  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>
      <fr:strong>Definition</fr:strong>
    </fr:p>
    <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P_n(x) = \frac {1}{2^n n!} \frac {d^n}{dx^n} {(x^2-1)}^n]]></fr:tex>
    <fr:p>
      <fr:strong>Properties</fr:strong>
    </fr:p>
    <fr:ul><fr:li>Legendre polnomials are orthogonal in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2([-1,1])]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Obtained by <fr:link type="external" href="Gram-Schmidt%20orthonormalization%20procedure">Gram-Schmidt orthonormalization procedure</fr:link> of the monomials</fr:li>
<fr:li>The set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\left \{ \sqrt {\frac {2n+1}{2}} P_n(x), n \in  \mathbb {N} \right \}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link type="external" href="orthonormal%20basis">orthonormal basis</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2([-1,1])]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Legendre polynomials have definite parity <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P_n(-x) = (-1)^nP_n(x)]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
    <fr:p>
      <fr:strong>Applications</fr:strong>
    </fr:p>
    <fr:ul><fr:li>Expanding an inverse distance potential</fr:li>
<fr:li>They also appear when solving the Schr√∂dinger equation in three dimensions for a central force</fr:li>
<fr:li>In recurrent neural networks</fr:li></fr:ul>
